\par As well as informing pollinators the presence of flowers, colou
r also helps to advertise their nectar reward status. When a pollinator approaches, the flower gives off stimulatory signals, such as scent, to show the insect the way to the nectar site. The colour patterning of flowers directs the pollinator to the cent
re where the nectar is located, and thus enables fertilisation.}{\f0\fs22\up6\insrsid13135341 6}{\f0\fs22\insrsid13135341 
\par Plants too know about the guiding function of the colours they possess. In fact, they deceive animals by employing this feature in a most conscious manner. Some plants which have no nectar use
